<span id="freeTextContainer10504828558208762786"><b>2012 view</b>: Kundera (originally writing in French) puts together tales of Czech citizens opposing the communist regime using an unusual mixture of novel, short story collection and musings. As ever a great piece of work by Kundera, although a bit too literary / high falutin&apos; at times in my opinion. 7 out of 12<br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1588088498i/29370933._SX540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><b>2011 view</b>: This work by Milan Kundera, published in 1979 is composed of seven separate narratives united by some common themes. The book considers the nature of forgetting as it occurs in hi</span>
  <span id="freeText10504828558208762786" style="display:none"><b>2012 view</b>: Kundera (originally writing in French) puts together tales of Czech citizens opposing the communist regime using an unusual mixture of novel, short story collection and musings. As ever a great piece of work by Kundera, although a bit too literary / high falutin' at times in my opinion. 7 out of 12<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1588088498i/29370933._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>2011 view</b>: This work by Milan Kundera, published in 1979 is composed of seven separate narratives united by some common themes. The book considers the nature of forgetting as it occurs in history, politics and life in general. The stories also contain elements found in the genre of Magical Realism (a la Murakami). Salman Rushdie best explains it 'A whirling dance of a book... Kundera is a self confessed hedonist in a world beset by politics, and his marvellous novel mingles a hedonist's love of eroticism, fantasy and fun with knife-sharp political satire'. The book is set in the background of Communist ruled Czechoslovakia. 6 out of 12</span>
