        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/970853518?book_show_action=true">Jun 18, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Khashayar Mohammadi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Khashayar Mohammadi" href="/user/show/32374363-khashayar-mohammadi">Khashayar Mohammadi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32374363-khashayar-mohammadi?shelf=idiosyncratic">idiosyncratic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32374363-khashayar-mohammadi?shelf=czech-lit">czech-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32374363-khashayar-mohammadi?shelf=slavic-lit">slavic-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer970853518" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16840365687446784282">Kundera was my first ever literary hero. He was the very first writer I actively sought and worshiped. His titanic stature in my adolescence made me reluctant to re-read his works as an adult, and I gotta admit re-reading this book in my twenties was a strange experience. I&apos;m still enchanted by his unparalleled psychological incisiveness and para-philosophical escapades, but I just don&apos;t find him to be the behemoth he once was in my eyes.<br/><br/>Having read this a second time, I&apos;m more confused than imp</span>
  <span id="freeText16840365687446784282" style="display:none">Kundera was my first ever literary hero. He was the very first writer I actively sought and worshiped. His titanic stature in my adolescence made me reluctant to re-read his works as an adult, and I gotta admit re-reading this book in my twenties was a strange experience. I'm still enchanted by his unparalleled psychological incisiveness and para-philosophical escapades, but I just don't find him to be the behemoth he once was in my eyes.<br /><br />Having read this a second time, I'm more confused than impressed by his strange symbolism and fourth wall breaks. I still believe this is a great book and one of his finest, it all comes down to how open the reader is to Kundera's eccentricities. I personally consider this book to be the most "French" novel he wrote. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16840365687446784282" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


