<span id="freeTextContainer15312804592906804880">&quot;The struggle of man against power is the struggle of memory against forgetting.&quot;<br/><br/>“The stupidity of people comes from having an answer for everything. The wisdom of the novel comes from having a question for everything....The novelist teaches the reader to comprehend the world as a question. There is wisdom and tolerance in that attitude. In a world built on sacrosanct certainties the novel is dead. The totalitarian world, whether founded on Marx, Islam, or anything else, is a world of answers ra</span>
  <span id="freeText15312804592906804880" style="display:none">"The struggle of man against power is the struggle of memory against forgetting."<br /><br />“The stupidity of people comes from having an answer for everything. The wisdom of the novel comes from having a question for everything....The novelist teaches the reader to comprehend the world as a question. There is wisdom and tolerance in that attitude. In a world built on sacrosanct certainties the novel is dead. The totalitarian world, whether founded on Marx, Islam, or anything else, is a world of answers rather than questions. There, the novel has no place"<br /><br />These words are not from me but from the novel itself. <br /></span>
