<div id="review_11014425" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/11014425" />
    <a title="Giuseppe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/714380-giuseppe"><img alt="Giuseppe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1306879881p2/714380.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/11014425?book_show_action=true">Dec 25, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Giuseppe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Giuseppe" href="/user/show/714380-giuseppe">Giuseppe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">activists, poets, philosophers, the high minded, sociologists</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer11014425" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2078260471000533538">Kundera again fascinates with his matter of fact, take it like it is, humorous and utterly intellectual writing style propped up, again, by the historical event that must have rattled his life experience the most: the Prague Spring Revolution of 1968. I love this book. It is thought provoking, humorous and at times arousingly-erotic. These facts fail to impede the authors ability to carry a dead serious undercurrent important to the overall experience he seeks to share in this narrative. Kundera</span>
  <span id="freeText2078260471000533538" style="display:none">Kundera again fascinates with his matter of fact, take it like it is, humorous and utterly intellectual writing style propped up, again, by the historical event that must have rattled his life experience the most: the Prague Spring Revolution of 1968. I love this book. It is thought provoking, humorous and at times arousingly-erotic. These facts fail to impede the authors ability to carry a dead serious undercurrent important to the overall experience he seeks to share in this narrative. Kundera has a gift for writing others' perspectives that may or may not be his own, which adds immensely to the reading experience.<br /><br />His philosophical proclivities are as provocative as they are applicable to this modern age. The narrative's collected within fantastically interweave in a manner few writers can accomplish. Fewer still can accomplish well. Kundera achieves the latter! <br /><br />One quote I will share here might be the most marvelously indignant critique of the blogosphere and hypercommunication age, which this very website is a spawn of: <i>Once the writer in every individual comes to life (and that time is not far off), we are in for an age of universal deafness and lack of understanding</i>. <br />This prophetic critique has ricocheted through the annals of history to strike a mighty blow against the hull of today, for this stupendous book was published in 1979.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2078260471000533538" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


