<div id="review_101240139" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/101240139" />
    <a title="K.D. Absolutely" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2156200-k-d-absolutely"><img alt="K.D. Absolutely" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471967140p2/2156200.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/101240139?book_show_action=true">May 04, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K.D. Absolutely" class="user" itemprop="url" name="K.D. Absolutely" href="/user/show/2156200-k-d-absolutely">K.D. Absolutely</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to K.D. by: </span>
      1001 Books You Must Read Before You Die (2006-2010)
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2156200-k-d-absolutely?shelf=1001-core">1001-core</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer101240139" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4548000490334378483">I am sure that Milan Kundera (born 1929) will someday get his Nobel prize for literature. This is my 2nd book by him and he still amused me with his Nietzsche-inspired style of writing. This book, <i>A Book of Laughter and Forgetting</i> in some ways foreshadows his most popular work, my first read of him, <i>The Unbearable Lightness of Being</i>. I prefer <i>Unbearable</i> though because it has one plot and one or maybe two themes: that people belong to either lightness or heaviness and that we are living in an inf</span>
  <span id="freeText4548000490334378483" style="display:none">I am sure that Milan Kundera (born 1929) will someday get his Nobel prize for literature. This is my 2nd book by him and he still amused me with his Nietzsche-inspired style of writing. This book, <i>A Book of Laughter and Forgetting</i> in some ways foreshadows his most popular work, my first read of him, <i>The Unbearable Lightness of Being</i>. I prefer <i>Unbearable</i> though because it has one plot and one or maybe two themes: that people belong to either lightness or heaviness and that we are living in an infinite universe so everything is guaranteed to recur infinitely.<br /><br />In <i>Laughter and Forgetting</i>, there are 7 short stories, mostly with different set of characters and different plots. The book itself says that there is a single plot interweaving the seven stories and that the main character in Chapter 4 <i>Lost Letters</i>, <b>Tamina</b> has her life reflected in all those 7 stories. I am just a simple reader, who had only 3 units of World Literature in college, and currently working in Information Technology, so maybe it is beyond me to interpret what's with Tamina's character that is being reflected by the other 6 stories. I just cannot get it.<br /><br />However, I still like this book because I love novels when I am free to interpret them. Kundera tells his story and leave the reader to take away what they want from it. Oh, he has many, many metaphors and allusions here and I just didn't know anymore which one to remember and which one to just brush aside. For example, Chapter 5 <i>Litost</i> just did not make any sense to me. Kundera gave many examples and he says that he could not find an exactly translation of this word in any language but still I do not see its relavance on Tamina. However, towards the end of the last page of Chapter 7 <i>The Border</i> anyway, when <b>Jan</b> is seeing the naked men and women, he thought about the holocaust prisoners in the concentration camp. Since I am free to interpret the book, I would rather associate this with holocaust and that justifies the 3 stars that I decided to give this book.<br /><br />Otherwise, that rating is but too generous, in my opinion only. I can see how other people would love this book, though. It makes you think. Think a lot while reading. It has that aftertaste of Murakami's magical realism (I cannot say G. G. Marquez's) but maybe I am Asian so I prefer that of Murakami's because he uses locales and beliefs that are more familiar to me. <br /><br />Overall, this is a good imaginative book and still a joy to read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4548000490334378483" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

